<TEXT>
in a city known for its brusqueness where 
officeholders are often loud and brash david dinkins comes across 
as something of an anomaly a gentleman politician 
dinkins the manhattan borough president defeated mayor edward 
i koch for the democratic mayoral nomination on tuesday thus 
earning a chance to become the citys first black mayor if he can 
outpoll republican rudolph giuliani in november 
he is a cautious and thoughtful politician a healer and 
conciliator and consensusbuilder according to his supporters 
a quiet man who reaches out to people said state attorney 
general robert abrams 
even opponents like the contentious koch concede that dinkins 
is a very decent guy 
but they question whether a nice guy can run a city facing a 
myriad of difficult problems stand up to special interests fighting 
over its 27 billion budget and ride herd over its more than 
200000 employees 
he has been careful to the point of timidity and his indecision 
sometimes frustrates his colleagues the new york times said of 
dinkins when it endorsed koch 
dinkins 62 has been in public life for more than two decades 
although he says he was hopelessly hooked on politics from his 
first race he does not have a reputation as being driven or a big 
risktaker 
ive never had the ambition particularly to be the citys first 
black mayor he said last year he announced his decision to run 
after forming a committee to examine what was needed for a mayoral 
bid a step that was derided by some 
a trenton nj native he graduated in 1950 from howard 
university with a mathematics degree he moved to harlem in 1951 and 
was married two years later 
he graduated from brooklyn law school in 1956 got involved in 
democratic politics and was elected to one term in the state 
assembly in 1965 
he served as city clerk for 10 years until he won the borough 
presidency in 1985 on his third attempt 
the citys highest elected black officeholder dinkins has stuck 
to his middleoftheroad approach in the citys often seething 
cauldron of racial and ethnic politics 
he has been outspoken against apartheid in south africa yet was 
slow to comment on the tawana brawley case when he did he was 
critical of her advisers he also has denounced statements by louis 
farrakhan as antisemitic 
in a display of independence he supported jesse jacksons 1984 
presidential bid when other black leaders backed walter mondale 
jackson returned the favor by coming to new york twice to campaign 
for dinkins 
one problem that has haunted dinkins was the four years 196871 
when he said he forgot to pay his income taxes 
he brushes off questions about that now saying it was an 
oversight that he has rectified 
he chooses instead to talk about his record as borough president 
on such issues as housing and homelessness aids services infant 
mortality and education 
of average height and with a slight paunch he exudes confidence 
and carries himself in a reserved and dignified manner hes an avid 
tennis player with a mean forehand even though hes a grandfather 
ive been described as a nice guy as a gentleman dinkins 
said last february but im also an exmarine and i dont intend 
for a second to get shoved around in this or any other campaign 
</TEXT>
