<TEXT>
tomato lovers who shop at farm markets or have 
backyard patches of their own are nearing the time of autumnal gloom 
it descends with the first killing frost and nothing will 
suffice until next year not tomatoes shipped from mexico or the 
warm southern areas of the united states 
soaring tomato prices were a major contributor to a sharp rise in 
consumer food costs last winter says the agriculture department 
retail vegetable prices which had been expected to ease in the 
first quarter of 1989 rose an average of 57 percent 
much of that increase was blamed on cold weather in mexico 
florida and california which cut supplies of fresh vegetables 
including tomatoes there was also some lingering effect from last 
years searing drought 
in the first half of 1989 prices paid to commercial tomato 
growers averaged more than 41 per 100 pounds up from 26 during 
the same period of last year 
a late january freeze in mexico slowed shipments to us 
consumers and boosted retail tomato prices by 48 percent in the 
first quarter a freeze in florida in late february damaged the 
newly planted spring crop and added further problems 
prices paid to us tomato growers rose to a record of 5580 per 
100 pounds in april and retail prices averaged a record 132 per 
pound in may 
gary lucier of the departments economic research service said 
august figures show tomato prices at the farm dropped to less than 
half of the earlier record level 
were in better shape now lucier said monday in a telephone 
interview we could see some fluctuations up and down for the next 
few months but typically if there arent any freezes i dont 
see any problem 
after peaking in may at the record retail price of 132 per 
pound nationally consumers by june saw tomatoes ease back to 87 
cents per pound as new seasonal supplies took hold 
and then it was time for locally grown produce to make its market 
entry the tomatoes melons sweet corn squash and other items 
that headline thousands of roadside stands and farm markets each 
summer 
even the industry recognizes that in the summertime anyway 
theres a lull in demand for tomatoes because of home gardens 
lucier said prices are typically at their low point 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the us sheep flock has increased slightly in 
recent years but still is one of the smallest inventories since the 
agriculture department began keeping track in 1867 global sheep 
numbers meanwhile are at record levels 
currently the worlds sheep flock is estimated at 1145 billion 
head up 2 percent from a year ago according to a report by the 
departments economic research service most of the increase is in 
china australia and the european economic community 
the us flock of sheep and lambs as of jan 1 was estimated 
earlier this year at 108 million head up fractionally from a year 
earlier inventories have been declining generally for many years 
since a peak of 562 million in 1942 
as a result the us wool clip has also been relatively small 
although the 1988 production of shorn wool increased 5 percent from 
1987 to 892 million pounds 
comparatively us mills used about 352 million pounds of wool 
in the second quarter of this year down slightly from januarymarch 
but up about 4 percent from the second quarter of 1988 the report 
said 
with mill use up wool imports have risen totaling 319 million 
pounds in the second quarter of 1989 up nearly 10 percent from 
januarymarch and 26 percent more than in the same period of last 
year 
australia new zealand and the united kingdom are major suppliers 
the 198889 world output of wool is estimated at a record 712 
billion pounds on a greasy or uncleaned basis up by more than 2 
percent from last year the report said 
most of this increase occurred in australia the main source of 
apparel wool entering export trade where excellent pasture 
conditions and large sheep numbers caused 198889 production to be 
almost 209 billion pounds greasy 36 percent above the previous 
season the report said china and argentina also experienced 
larger production 
new zealand the major source of coarser grades of wool used in 
carpets blankets and heavy clothing reported a decline in 
production because of droughtrelated lower yields and fewer sheep 
