<TEXT>
a capital gains tax cut endorsed by president 
bush is drawing fire from liberal economists who call it an unfair 
windfall for the rich that will worsen the deficit and do nothing to 
stimulate savings 
it is at best a budgetary quick fix with harmful longterm 
consequences five economists said in a letter to congress monday 
it is at worst yet another shell game which will redistribute the 
nations wealth toward those already most welloff 
one of the five lawrence summers of harvard university said the 
proposal may well be the worst tax idea in the history of the 
republic 
the criticism came as the house ways and means committee prepared 
to resume consideration of the proposed capital gains cut the most 
recent unofficial count indicated that all 13 republicans on the 
committee and six democrats a bare majority favored the proposal 
the committees democratic leadership has been delaying a vote on 
the cut sponsored chiefly by reps ed jenkins dga and bill 
archer rtexas 
rep dan rostenkowski dill who opposes a reduction has 
drafted a substitute in hopes of knocking down the bushendorsed 
jenkinsarcher plan aides say rostenkowski is broadening his 
proposal so the reduction would apply to some assets already held 
the committee expects to take a final vote this week 
capital gains which are profits from the sale of stock land and 
other assets are taxed at the same rates as wages and other income 
bush says a capital gains cut would stimulate the economy and 
increase revenue collections by encouraging taxpayers to cash in 
longheld investments 
under the jenkinsarcher plan the 33 percent maximum tax rate 
would be cut to 196 percent for capital gains for 2 years it then 
would be raised to 28 percent and indexed so that profits caused 
solely by inflation would not be taxed 
democrats in congress generally oppose a capital gains reduction 
their main arguments presented monday in writing by the five 
economists were 
eighty percent of the benefits from the jenkinsarcher bill 
would go to those with incomes over 100000 a year 
noting that the 1986 tax overhaul sharply reduced all tax rates 
by taking away preferences for capital gains and other deductions 
the economists wrote to restore that preference now would leave 
the tax system tilted unconscionably toward those who already enjoy 
the greatest share of our nations bounty 
because the reduction would be temporary it will reward those 
who have already made profitable investments and not at all those 
who must choose whether to invest in the future 
from a budget standpoint a capital gains tax cut is a clear 
loser after a quick surge revenues will fall 
as to stimulating savings the economists wrote evidence is 
completely lacking that a cut in tax rates on capital gains will 
have any effect on savings 
three of the economists attended a news conference hosted by 
reps donald pease dohio and sander levin dmich ways and 
means members who oppose a reduction 
summers joseph minarik executive director of congress joint 
economic committee and henry aaron of the brookings institution 
spoke at the news conference also signing the letter were alan 
auerbach and alan blinder chairmen of the economics departments at 
respectively university of pennsylvania and princeton university 
meanwhile another ways and means member who opposes a capital 
gains cut rep byron l dorgan dnd sought to deny any benefit 
from such a reduction to those with incomes over 200000 a year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

