federal regulators are seeking millions of 
dollars in restitution from two commodity options firms charged with 
misleading their customers about risky investments 
siegel trading company inc based in chicago and international 
trading group ltd with headquarters in san mateo calif were 
sued separately monday by the commodity futures trading commission 
this is probably the largest antifraud sales solicitation case 
the cftc has ever brought said dennis klejna director of the 
commissions enforcement division 
the suits were filed in us district court for the central 
district of california accused the firms of charging clients 45 
percent commissions while giving investors advice they knew or 
should have known was wrong or incomplete 
both lawsuits seek preliminary injunctions barring the firms from 
continuing their alleged illegal practices klejna said the cftc 
also would seek to have the firms return all profits made through 
illegal practices 
a spokesman for chicagobased siegel was not in his office when 
called for comment and did not return a reporters phone call monday 
evening 
in san mateo calif itg issued a statement saying it was 
reviewing the charges but intended to fight them vigorously itg 
sales practices comply with applicable law and regulation do not 
mislead potential or actual customers and are proper in all 
respects it said 
itg also said it is not connected in any way with siegel 
options are contracts that give their owners the right to conduct 
a specified transaction such as buying or selling a certain number 
of shares of a given common stock at a set price within a stated 
period of time usually just a few months 
options can be highly risky and since they are usually shortterm 
investment vehicles they involve a lot of buying and selling for 
which commissions must be paid each time 
in the itg case the cftc said that between jan 1 1984 and may 
31 1989 more than 85 percent of the firms customers lost a total 
of 428 million 283 million of it in commissions collected by itg 
in the other case from jan 1 1984 until the present about 85 
percent of siegels customers lost money totaling 336 million 
for the same period the firm took in 40 million in commissions 
