the 17nation european jewish congress has endorsed 
suspending formal contact between jewish groups and the roman 
catholic church because of the dispute over a convent at the 
auschwitz death camp in poland 
at issue is the word of the church it is difficult to speak 
with someone when you have this kind of problem said theo klein 
who led the french delegation monday at the annual meeting 
klein a former president of the european jewish congress said 
he has appealed to jewish organizations to suspend official contacts 
with the catholic church he said there had been no dissent 
each organization is free to make its own policy so i cannot 
say to you that all organizations have stopped dialogue but i think 
so said klein who helped negotiate a 1987 pact with catholic 
leaders to remove the carmelite convent 
the meeting was dominated by the convent issue which has split 
catholics and revived debates about lingering antisemitism in 
europe 
many jews regard the convent at the camp where at least 25 
million jews were among the estimated 4 million victims during world 
war ii as offensive 
under the 1987 accord negotiated between jewish representatives 
and officials of the catholic church including polish cardinal 
franciszek macharski it was agreed the convent should be removed by 
feb 22 
but the polish primate cardinal jozef glemp continues to back 
the convent which was intalled in 1984 in a hut where the nazis 
stored gas used to murder jews and other inmates 
glemp has said the geneva agreement was not negotiated by 
competent people and after summer protests by jewish activists 
at the convent angered jews and nonjews alike with remarks many 
people consider antisemitic 
