<TEXT>
researchers at brookhaven national 
laboratory have created energy using a new method for 
hightemperature nuclear fusion that may have the potential for 
producing a clean and efficient form of nuclear energy 
i would classify this as a new approach that has not been tried 
by anybody else before there may be promise dr robert beuhler 
a chemist at the laboratory on new yorks long island said monday 
he said the new method involves the firing of a cluster of up to 
1300 fuel molecules at a stationary fuel target the resulting 
compression causes atoms from the cluster and the target to fuse 
producing a small burst of nuclear energy 
we were quite surprised beuhler said on behalf of himself 
senior chemist dr lewis friedman and another colleague dr gerhart 
friedlander 
but the researchers enthusiasm was tempered by the realization 
that it would take years of further work to verify whether fusion 
can be achieved on a much larger scale 
this is very new ground beuhler said 
beuhler said the method produces a small burst of nuclear energy 
only once in every 10 billion times it is tried 
the work to create nuclear fusion began in the spring financed 
by the federal energy department cluster research at brookhaven has 
gone on for more than a decade 
the findings were accepted for publication in the sept 18 issue 
of the journal physical review letters he said in a telephone 
interview 
researchers did not formally announce their findings because they 
felt it was too early to tell how the new process will do at higher 
temperatures and with other variables 
he said scientists can achieve fusion now in a hydrogen bomb but 
he added with a chuckle its not very controlled 
in the brookhaven experiments the fuel consisted of tiny 
clusters of molecules of heavy water whose hydrogen had been 
replaced by a heavier isotope deuterium which is commonly found in 
sea water 
the clusters he said were electrically charged and speeded up 
before being fired at a solid target of atoms the clusters heated 
and compressed at impact setting off the burst of nuclear energy 
this is really stellar research heating up a large number of 
atoms to the temperatures that exist in stars beuhler said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

