<TEXT>
the state department strengthened its ban on 
sugar imports from panama today by denying that country any share of 
a quota increase being allocated to sugarexporting countries 
in addition the department said the administration is expanding 
the list of panamanian companies and individuals affiliated with the 
panamanian government to which americans cannot make payments 
spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said the actions are a direct 
result of the continued unwillingness of gen manuel antonio noriega 
to respect the will of the panamanian people by stepping down and 
permitting the installation of a freely elected government 
as part of the economic sanctions the united states imposed 
against the central american country last year panamas sugar quota 
was suspended and cost the panamanian government 15 million in 
revenues ms tutwiler said 
panamas share of a general quota increase announced by the 
office of the special trade representative would have been 23403 
tons she added 
ms tutwiler had no additional information on the expanded list 
of panamanian companies and individuals to which the americans 
cannot make payments 
the administration has refrained from imposing sanctions on china 
after the crackdown on the prodemocracy movement on grounds that 
such action would hurt the chinese people asked why the 
administration does not apply the same rationale to panama ms 
tutwiler said noriega is hurting the panamanian people more by 
refusing to step down 
the administration took the new actions 12 days after 
noriegadominated council of state selected a longtime noriega 
associate to be panamas unelected president 
at the time the administration said it would have no diplomatic 
dealings with the new leadership 
