<TEXT>
the tiny deer tick blamed for spreading 
lyme disease also carries another disease that has sickened at 
least five people in southeastern connecticut in the past year 
state health officials say 
the disease babesiosis is relatively rare and is caused by the 
infection of red blood cells with a parasitic protozoan a 
microscopic animal called babesia microti said matthew j cartter 
state epidemiologist in the state department of health services 
symptoms develop in about one to four weeks after exposure and 
include fever chills fatigue anorexia headache sweating muscle 
and joint pain and nausea he said 
health officials issued a warning monday as part of their effort 
to get doctors to report all cases of babesiosis 
there have been fewer than 200 confirmed cases of the disease in 
the united states in the past 10 years said eric mintz an 
epidemiologist for the federal centers for disease controls 
connecticut station 
most cases have been reported from nantucket island and marthas 
vineyard in massachusetts shelter island and fire island in new 
york block island in rhode island and wisconsin 
until 1988 only one case had been reported in a connecticut 
resident who did not acquire the disease in one of those areas 
although babesiosis is less of a risk to public health than lyme 
disease it is lifethreatening in people whose spleens do not 
function or those with other conditions that result in a suppressed 
immune system health officials said the infection is more severe 
in elderly people and in infants they said 
mintz said that unlike lyme disease babesiosis will not cause 
longterm or recurring health problems to those in good health 
lyme disease causes a rash or aches and pains and a lowgrade 
fever followed by arthritislike pain in the joints or nerve damage 
causing pain or numbness 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

