<TEXT>
in a highly unusual move the 
government tuesday said it would allow a mass march condemning 
alleged brutality by police riot squads protest marches in south 
africa normally are outlawed 
anglican archbishop desmond tutu and other organizers of 
wednesdays demonstration had refused to seek authorization from the 
government but acting president fw de klerk told reporters the 
protest would be allowed nonetheless because of assurances that it 
would be peaceful 
i hope tomorrow will prove that a new spirit can arise in our 
beautiful country a spirit in which all christians and all people 
who say that they believe in peace will reach out and really start 
talking to each other de klerk said 
the march through downtown cape town is to coincide with the 
opening of parliament where the national partycontrolled electoral 
college is expected to elect de klerk to a fiveyear term thursday 
he has offered to negotiate a new constitution that would give some 
form of political rights to the nowvoteless black majority 
tutu and other activists allege that at least 23 people in cape 
towns black and mixedrace townships were killed on the night of 
the sept 6 parliamentary elections by police police say 15 people 
were killed 10 in blackonblack faction fighting 
de klerk said police were forced to act because militants were 
forcefully preventing people from voting he said remedial steps 
would be taken on any policemen found to have used excessive force 
this is not the time to aggravate the differences that exist in 
