<TEXT>
a divided senate voted tuesday to confirm 
donald gregg as ambassador to south korea dismissing claims that 
his repeated denials of involvement in the irancontra affair are 
absurd on their face 
the vote was 66 to 33 fortyfive republicans and 21 democrats 
voted for the gregg nomination while 33 democrats voted against it 
greggs gop defenders contended his democratic foes were using 
the nominee in a desperate attempt to attempt revive the irancontra 
furor and attack president bush who nominated his close associate 
for the job 
but one democrat sen charles robb dva said he too had 
concluded gregg was blameless and would support the nomination out 
of conscience and conviction 
robb discounted greggs links to the irancntra affair and 
mounted a 45minute pointbypoint defense 
shortly before the vote senate majority leader george mitchell 
of maine said he had reached the opposite conclusion because the 
explanations offered by him are so inconsistent with the known facts 
that they cannot be believed 
even if it was proved that gregg told nothing but the truth his 
nomination should still be rejected because his testimony casts 
serious doubt on his judgment mitchell said 
gregg a 30year veteran of the central intelligence agency who 
once was cia station chief in seoul served in bushs vice 
presidential office as his chief foreign policy adviser 
the gregg nomination has been pending since early march in two 
sessions before the senate foreign relations committee gregg 
denied under oath allegations he was ever involved in the secret 
and illegal effort to resupply the contra rebels in nicaragua 
the sharply divided panel eventually voted 127 to recommend the 
full senate confirm the nomination 
mr gregg has clearly not been straight with us said sen 
alan cranston dcalif as debate opened in the senate few who 
have reviewed the record have come away with any confidence in mr 
greggs veracity 
cranston told his colleagues if we were to promote a man we 
believed to have misled us under oath we would invite contempt for 
our inquiries we would encourage frustration of our constitutional 
obligations 
cranston has led the attempt to sidetrack or defeat the gregg 
nomination in his position as chairman of the asian affairs 
subcommitee 
sen albert gore dtenn scoffed at greggs explanation why 
bushs agenda for two separate meetings as vice president included 
the subject of contra resupply 
gregg testified they were typos and should have read copter 
resupply referring to an issue involving helicopters for the 
armed forces in el salvador 
what does he take the senate for and what do we take him for 
gore asked are we to seriously accept a baldfaced presentation 
of that kind its absurd on its face 
to vote to confirm we have to believe this nominee did not lie 
brazenly and repeatedly gore said its a little difficult to 
swallow 
gregg testified he never informed bush about a warning he 
received about the resupply operation until after he gave an 
interview about it to reporters of the new york times 
he would have us believe that his boss read about it in the 
paper gore said it appears that he may have been prepared to 
preserve deniability for his boss and he was prepared to go to 
extraordinary lengths to do so 
