<TEXT>
anton lubowski the only white to hold a 
leadership post in the southwest africa peoples organization 
guerrilla movement was assassinated tuesday outside his home in 
suburban windhoek police said 
lt kierie du rand a police spokesman said lubowksi was shot in 
the head at about 850 pm by an assailant who drove away in a red 
sedan du rand said an allout manhunt had been launched 
lubowski 37 was an unofficial spokesman for swapo the namibian 
independence movement that had waged a bush war against south 
african rule of the territory since 1966 
south africa has agreed to grant independence expected by early 
next year as part of a regional peace accord also calling for 
withdrawal of cuban troops from angola 
lubowski was also a member of swapos election directorate which 
is overseeing the movements campaign for unsupervised elections 
scheduled for early november swapo is favored to win most votes in 
the election but it needs a twothirds majority to control the 
drafting of a constitution 
the assassination occurred just two days before the scheduled 
homecoming of swapo president sam nujoma who has been in exile for 
30 years 
a police officer at the scene said lubowski was killed by several 
shots fired at close range from a sovietmade ak47 automatic rifle 
ak47s were used by swapo during the bush war and could be 
obtained through contacts either with the guerrilla movement or with 
the security forces which captured numerous weapons 
a neighbor said the person who fired the gun got back into a car 
carrying at least one other person but there was no description of 
the attackers 
the south africanappointed administrator of namibia louis 
pienaar expressed shock at the killing and said the authorities 
will not allow circumstances of anarchy to develop in the runup 
to the election 
pienaar said the assassination was part of a spiral of 
violence that included the fatal stoning of a white police officer 
over the weekend by a crowd of blacks 
lubowksi studied at stellenbsch and cape town universities two 
of south africas best at one point an officer in the south african 
army lubowski a lawyer joined swapos legal political wing in 
1984 
although his law practice was in windhoek he represented many 
antiapartheid activists in trials in south africa 
he recently helped defend 14 blacks convicted of murdering a 
black policeman in 1985 they were sentenced to hang under the 
doctrine of common purpose which held them responsible even 
though only one contributed physically to the policemans death 
last week south africas appeals court granted the socalled 
upington 14 the right to appeal their death sentences 
lubowski was divorced his two children live with his exwife in 
south africa 
the namibianborn lubowski had received numerous death threats 
since joining swapo said gwen mckinney director of the namibia 
information office in washington 
she said lubowski who had installed an elaborate security system 
in his house died at the scene 
