<TEXT>
the bush administration plans to propose to 
congress that the united states next year accept 50000 soviet 
refugees plus 6500 more from eastern europe a us official and 
sources in the american jewish community said tuesday 
worldwide 125000 refugees would be admitted an increase of 
slightly less than 8 percent from this year 
the 50000 soviet refugees at least half of whom are expected to 
be jews are a fraction of the 250000 soviet citizens the state 
department estimated last week would apply for entry to the united 
states in 1990 
of the 50000 the sources said 40000 would have their 
transportation and settlement costs paid by the united states the 
10000 others would have to depend on private organizations friends 
and relatives 
this years combined quota for refugees from the soviet union and 
eastern europe is 50000 the new plan would allocate 50000 slots 
to the soviet union and set up a separate category of 6500 for 
eastern europe 
last year as emigration from the soviet union began to climb 
the combined quota for the soviet union and eastern europe was 
15000 
jewel s lafontant the state departments refugee affairs 
coordinator is scheduled to testify to a house judiciary 
subcommittee wednesday about the administration proposal 
an estimated 40000 soviet jews are expected to leave the soviet 
union this year currently there is a backlog of an estimated 30000 
to 40000 jews with exit permits for israel who have not left the 
soviet union or are in vienna and rome seeking entry to the united 
states 
most soviet jews who obtain exit permits say they want to live in 
israel all but a fraction however then apply for admission to the 
united states once they have left their country 
according to the jewish sources who demanded anonymity the bush 
administration will also drastically revise its processing 
procedures tentatively refugees who apply before oct 1 the 
beginning of the 1990 fiscal year will be processed in rome and 
vienna 
thereafter applications will be handled by a beefedup us 
embassy staff in moscow and by a new office to be set up outside 
washington 
the us official who also asked not to be named said that the 
oct 1 cutoff date was very likely but that it might be set back a 
few months 
while the soviets seeking admission remain in their country 
their applications would be considered both in moscow and in the 
washington area office 
israel has expressed concern that jewish refugees from the soviet 
union were increasingly choosing to head for the united states once 
out of their homeland depriving the jewish state of needed settlers 
it was not clear whether the change in us procedure would 
increase the flow of refugees to israel 
the rising exodus from the soviet union which results from us 
pressure as well as reforms undertaken by president mikhail s 
gorbachev poses administrative and financial problems for the bush 
administration 
eager to reinforce the right of soviet citizens to travel freely 
us officials stress they will keep the door to immigrants open 
but beyond the 50000 slots allotted for the soviet union 
prospective jewish emigres will be encouraged to apply for parole 
status this requires private support for the immigrants 
also the sources said in admitting 50000 refugees from the 
soviet union preference will be given to those with close relatives 
here but no applicant will be declared ineligble on the grounds he 
has no relative here the officials said 
rep bruce morrison dconn who heads the house subcommittee on 
immigration said as hearings opened that the administrations 
proposal provides financing for 84000 of the 125000 refugees 
overall 
where do we get the money for the rest he asked a panel of 
private witnesses 
morrison also expressed concern about the backlog of emigres in 
rome and vienna awaiting us decisions on their eligibility to 
enter the united states he said the administration had wasted money 
through this processing method and changes would have to be 
considered 
</TEXT>
