<TEXT>
treasury secretary nicholas brady on tuesday 
warned that america was in danger of losing out in international 
competition unless the country did something about its inadequate 
savings rate and american businesses stopped chasing after quick 
profits 
bradys comments represented the opening salvo in what is 
expected to be a major new intiative on the part of the bush 
administration to boost americas competitive standing in the world 
traditionally the whole american workforce from the 
boardrooms to the factory floors shared a pride in their work 
unequaled in the world brady said however in recent years we 
have neglected our traditional strengths and have seen the other 
nations move forward to challenge our position in the world 
economy 
in remarks to 100 of the countrys top business executives 
gathered for dinner in the treasury departments ornate cash room 
brady decried what he saw as an emphasis on shortterm gains and a 
loss of commitment to plan for the future 
weve been willing to mortgage our future to sacrifice quality 
and to cut corners in the pursuit of the immediate payoff brady 
said it worries me when i see many of the best minds in america 
concentrating on financial engineering rather than laying plans for 
sound corporate strategies for the future 
brady told the business leaders that the president considered the 
problem one of his top priorities but he conceded in answer to a 
question that the administration had not yet resolved the question 
of how to offer tax breaks to increase savings without worsening the 
governments budget deficit 
he said the president hoped to have concrete proposals to offer 
in the area of boosting savings when he presents his next budget to 
congress in january 
if you set goals and have the backing of the president then you 
can do some things that are pretty amazing brady said making a 
pitch to the business leaders to support the administrations effort 
we must work together to find new ways to encourage americans 
to take the longterm view in their economic thinking as we work to 
preserve americas economic leadership and our standard of living 
he said 
bradys remarks were to a dinner meeting of the american business 
conference composed of the chief executive officers of 100 of the 
fastest growing companies in the nation 
earlier in the year the group produced its own study which 
singled out a decline in the personal savings rate as the biggest 
economic problem facing the united states and the chief cause of its 
huge trade deficits 
in his speech brady said that the administration was considering 
ways to boost the personal savings rate as a way of increasing the 
pool of funds from which businesses could borrow to make longterm 
investment 
if we provided for more of our domestic investment needs with 
our savings wed have to import less capital from abroad thus 
improving our trade balance brady said 
while brady did not spell out what options were being considered 
other treasury officials have said the administration is examining 
the possibility of broadening the use of taxdeferred individual 
retirement accounts the 1986 tax law sharply curbed ira tax 
benefits for workers who made more than 40000 a year and were 
covered by a company retirement plan 
brady said the administration would be looking at a number of 
options that give people the incentive to save instead of to 
consume 
brady said the administration was also considering proposing the 
removal of the current double taxation on dividends earned by a 
companys stockholders brady such a change would lower the cost of 
capital for american businesses and end the bias of the tax system 
toward debt financing by corporations 
at present companies pay dividends to shareholders out of 
aftertax profits and shareholders are also taxed on the dividends 
as well in the speech brady did not suggest how the government 
would make up the lost revenue from eliminating this double 
taxation an amount estimated to be as much as 40 billion a year 
brady also put in a plug for the administrations proposal to 
permanently reduce the capital gains tax which he said would 
provide an important incentive for companies to make longterm 
investments and he praised the administrationcongressional accord 
on cutting the budget deficit to 100 billion in the upcoming fiscal 
year 
he said all of these efforts would be needed to increase 
americas competitiveness 
