procter amp gamble co claimed a victory today in 
a legal fight with three competitors in the cookie business 
announcing that the companies have agreed to pay pampg 125 million 
for violating its patent on crisp and chewy cookies 
procter amp gamble said keebler co nabisco brands inc and 
fritolay inc have agreed to pay pampg a total of 125 million which 
will be reflected as part of pampgs firstquarter earnings for fiscal 
198889 
the three companies agreed to a consent judgment signed by us 
district judge joseph longobardi in wilmington del where pampg had 
filed its lawsuits the company announced today 
the cincinnatibased pampg markets its crisp and chewy cookies 
under the name duncan hines the company filed separate lawsuits 
against keebler nabisco and fritolay in june 1984 the lawsuits 
were consolidated for court handling and had been scheduled to go to 
trial oct 2 
the settlement averts the need for trial and allows the companies 
to avoid trial costs 
the agreement states that pampgs patent is valid and enforceable 
the agreement prevents the three companies from infringing pampgs 
patent in the future pampg officials said 
pampg spokesman donald tassone refused today to say how much each 
of the three companies would be paying pampg individually he said the 
settlement agreement requires that the companies not divulge its 
terms publicly 
pampg introduced its readytoeat crisp and chewy cookies in 1983 
keebler nabisco and fritolay later introduced this same type of 
cookie pampg said keebler is a subsidiary of united biscuits plc of 
britain nabisco is part of rjr nabisco inc and fritolay is owned 
by pepsico inc 
the three companies altered the composition of their cookies 
after pampg sued tassone said they no longer sell cookies that pampg 
regards as violating its patent he said 
weve worked hard to prove were right and we won said john 
e pepper president of procter amp gamble we believe this judgment 
is a complete vindication of our rights under this patent 
