<TEXT>
the senate finance committee searched tuesday 
for ways to scale back catastrophicillness protection for retirees 
in a lastditch effort to prevent repeal of the program which has 
drawn the ire of many older americans 
there was a recognition that there certainly is the possibility 
of repeal sen lloyd bentsen dtexas chairman of the panel 
said after a closeddoor session with members there is no 
question in my mind that we are going to face an amendment on the 
senate floor to repeal catastrophic 
there apparently is even stronger sentiment in the house for 
repeal a fact made clear tuesday to the bush administration 
at the white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said president 
bush is feeling the heat from complaining retirees but is not 
sure that repeal is the best way to fix the program the 
administration prefers to work on changing the taxes that finance 
catastrophic care fitzwater said 
house republican whip newt gingrich of georgia who along with 
other gop leaders met with bush said he has noted a dramatic 
shift in the administrations willingness to amend the program 
we recognize the impact on the elderly fitzwater said we 
recognize their concern were working with congress searching 
for a way to mitigate the financial problems and save the program 
to stave off repeal bentsen said the committee is now 
attempting to strip away all but basic elements of the program to 
reduce costs to the minimum this could lead to elimination of most 
benefits for prescription drugs and for skilled nursing care the 
chairman said 
catastrophic illness coverage was enacted with fanfare last year 
to protect medicare beneficiaries from financial ruin brought on by 
the cost of serious illness everyone eligible for medicare is 
required to pay into the program 
the additional coverage is under heavy attack from two groups of 
retirees some who are covered by private and employerfinanced 
insurance and dont need catastrophiccare coverage and some who 
are higherincome americans having to pay for protection for those 
at the bottom of the economic scale 
responding to those protests the house ways and means committee 
already has voted to reduce benefits and the two taxes that finance 
the program 
about twothirds of the costs are paid by retirees whose incomes 
are high enough that they pay more than 150 a year in federal 
income taxes they must pay a surtax up to 800 of 15 percent of 
their income taxes about 40 percent of all retirees are liable for 
the surtax this year 
the remainder of the program is financed by a flat 4 monthly 
premium paid by all but the poorest of the 33 million people 
eligible for medicare 
the finance committee agreed informally last week that the surtax 
would be cut significantly that the flat monthly premium would not 
be changed and that beneficiaries would have to pay a bigger share 
of expenses for drugs and doctors bills before reimbursement under 
the catastrophiccare program begins 
tuesdays committee session indicated however that that 
apparently was not enough to mollify those who want repeal 
as a result bentsen said what we are trying to do is 
structure a bill with essential parts that gets it back to a 
morecatastrophic bill instead of the longterm benefits which 
seem to be exploding costs 
when catastrophicillness protection was enacted last year it 
was predicted to cost about 31 billion over five years the latest 
forecasts put that figure at 45 billion or more skillednursing 
benefits and prescription drugs are major factors in the escalation 
bentsen and senate republican leader bob dole of kansas a member 
of the committee complained that the administrations concern 
appears to be based mainly on budget considerations not on how 
catastrophicillness coverage or its repeal would affect older 
americans 
the program is based on an insurance concept so taxes to finance 
it are being collected at a faster rate than benefits are being 
paid as a result repeal would deprive the treasury of 4 billion 
to 7 billion this year and worsen the federal deficit by that 
amount 
unless the budget law is waived repeal of the program would 
require congress to raise taxes to make up for the revenue loss 
otherwise repeal would trigger acrosstheboard cuts in most 
federal programs 
</TEXT>
