nutrisystem inc filed a lawsuit tuesday 
accusing a former vice president of stealing a 30 million marketing 
plan when she went to work for a competitor weight watchers 
international 
the suit asks montgomery county common pleas court to bar weight 
watchers from competing with nutrisystem based in willow grove in 
the weightloss market 
the suit also asks the court to order weight watchers which is 
based in jericho ny to pay nutrisystem all profits derived from 
the information provided by jean bakken 
bakken was promoted to the new position of vice president for 
competitive marketing on aug 18 and resigned sept 5 to work in a 
similar position for weight watchers according to the suit 
weight watchers also tried to lure other nutrisystem management 
personnel the suit says 
at nutrisystem bakken was working on an 18month marketing plan 
and participated in meetings with don mcculloch and al dimarco 
senior officers and owners of the company involving confidential 
informtion the suit says 
when company officials searched bakkens office after her 
resignation they found that virtually all of the companys 
documents including confidential and proprietary materials 
previously supplied to or requested by bakken were missing 
according to the suit 
the company charges that she is unlawfully using or unlawfully 
intends to use such information for the benefit of weight watchers 
the suit saying bakken abused the confidential nature of her 
relationship with nutrisystem asks the court to bar her from 
working for weight watchers 
no one answered the phone tuesday afternoon at the pittsburgh 
offices of hj heinz co the parent company of weight watchers a 
phone number for bakken could not be located 
when a 52 billion company like heinz obtains valuable 
proprietary information from a 433 million company it is not only 
unlawful and unethical but could also cause nutrisystem 
irreparable harm mcculloch said in a news release 
